  "ncbi_mapping_notes": "NCBI Taxonomy is a biological classification (organism taxonomy) rather than a subject heading system. Its value is in the organism hierarchy \u2014 mapping species, genera, families, orders, classes, phyla, kingdoms. This maps to the 'about what organism' axis, orthogonal to the 'about what topic' axis of other sources. Cross-references from NCBI to other sources should be at the kingdom/phylum level (e.g., NCBI Arthropoda \u2194 OpenAlex Insect Science \u2194 LoC Entomology).",
  "methodology_notes": "Mapped NCBI taxonomic hierarchy to organismal categories, OpenAlex life science fields/subfields to topic categories, NASA GCMD biosphere/biology keywords, DOE OSTI life sciences group, LoC biology subtree, and UNESCO biology-related roots. 16 categories covering organism taxonomy through applied biotechnology. Special attention to NCBI's unique organism-based classification vs. other sources' topic-based classification."
